                      <td><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Impact, Arial Black" size="5">Latest 
                        News </font></font></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr valign="top"> 
                      <td class="border"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">
<a name=97></a>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td colspan=2><font color=#FFFFFF size="5" face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif">Lucas Licensing Official Response to Star Wars License Change</font></td></tr>
<tr><td><font color=#FFFFFF face="arial" size="2">DeckTech reports on Wed Jan 9 2002 </font></td><td align=right><font face="arial" size="2" color=#FFFFFF>DeckTech: Star Wars</font></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2><font color=#FFFFFF face="arial" size="2">Thank you for writing to express your feelings about our Star Wars CCG decision.  That decision was my responsibility, and I would like you to have a better understanding of how the decision was made.<br>
 <br>
I have worked for Lucasfilm for 21 years.  For the last 16 years, I have been in charge of all of our merchandising.  I have stayed with the company this long because I love Star Wars, and I know that millions of people throughout the world share that love.  Not every decision I have made has been right, but I can tell you that every product decision is motivated<br>
 first and foremost by whether it will result in a better experience for the fans of Star Wars.<br>
 <br>
Two years ago we began a painstaking process of figuring out what to do with the Star Wars CCG when the Decipher license expired at the end of 2001.  We<br>
 heard extensive presentations from Decipher and Wizards of the Coast, and we talked to many, many players and retailers.  We faced a very difficult decision because Decipher had done a great job with the Star Wars CCG and is a terrific company with many wonderful and talented people.  Wizards is also a great company and holds a very special position as the originator of the CCG format and the creator of Magic: The Gathering.  We were honored that they were interested in Star Wars and listened very carefully to what they as well as Decipher and the fans had to say.  After nine months of an exhaustive process, we came to the conclusion that Wizards had a better vision for the long-term future of Star Wars. That vision encompassed an<br>
 improved game that could broaden the player base by offering a multi-layered experience within a single game (as opposed to multiple games for different<br>
 audiences) and would be designed by Richard Garfield himself, and an<br>
 improved organized play system that would support players better than ever before.  <br>
 <br>
This was a very difficult decision given the strengths of both companies, our long history with Decipher, and the considerable investment that many players had already made in the existing games.  In the end, we felt we had<br>
 to do what was right for the fans in the long run, knowing that our decision would not be well received by everyone.  Sometimes change is hard to accept, but our experience has been that change can be a good thing, and a way of<br>
 encouraging greater creativity and innovation. <br>
 <br>
Wizards has been working diligently for more than a year to produce what we all hope will be a worthy successor to the original Star Wars CCG.  I am truly sorry that you are upset with this decision. All that I can ask at<br>
 this point is that you reserve final judgment until you have a chance to see the product when it launches in April. <br>
 <br>
In the meantime, while Decipher will not be producing any new Star Wars products, we expect their existing games to go on, and Decipher themselves have committed to do everything in their power to continue these games for as long as the player community wants to play them. <br>
 <br>
Howard Roffman<br>
President, Lucas Licensing<p><small>edited by DeckTech on Wed Jan 9 2002 </small><p><small>edited by DeckTech on Wed Jan 9 2002 </small></font></td></tr>
<tr><td align=right colspan=2><font face=arial size=1> <a href=send.php?di=/index.php&id=97 target="_blank">send to friend</a> | <a href=print.php?97 target="_blank">printer friendly</a></font></td></tr>
</table><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Test</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Scott</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>did he write this specificaly to decktech, david/neal? or was this just a general response reposted from another site somewhere?</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>edmund</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>You can express whatever opinion you want. Just limit the way you express that opinion to appropriate language. Thanks.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>David</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Apparently he wrote it to the Riders list.  I got it from Tim Guzman and Hisstka</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>neal</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Okay Mr. Roffman, just realize that WoTC has VERY big shoes to fill when it comes to this game. The mechanics are simply unparalled, as I have played Magic along with other card games. None of them have caught my interest the way SW:CCG has. I know Garfield is supposedly "the man" when it comes to games, just try to interact with the top level SW:CCG players and make sure that this game is a worthwhile replacement. Making a Star Wars card game that has longetivity AND brilliant gameplay is difficult, but if you spent enough time in the intial investment, and PAY ATTENTION to what the consumers of said product say, then you may just have a worthwhile replacement.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF><a href="mailto:maatt@hotmail.com">Matt Lush</a></font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Makes good sense to me.  People need to remember this is a Business.....</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Scott Poster</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>I saw how well the "various levels of gameplay" worked with Magic, it sucked. Their beginner crap was worthless and the base set advanced level hurt longtime experienced players. That is partially why I got out of Magic in the first place because wizards ideas sucked and now they have star wars. Well, at least l5r is not under their controll anymore.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Mr.Goofball</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Mr. Hoffman, this is pure rubbish. Yanking the plug on a sucessful and viable game wreaks of suspicion.  You admit to a sucessful run with Decipher, but fail to point out exactly what this vision is that WotC had over Decipher...  Also, what players were spoken to about this decision?    10 year-old Pokemon snots?!?!?  C'mon.  Admit it; you wanted to have Lucas Licensing hold all the cards (literally and figuratively) under one Meglo-company...  Like Mr. Lush said, Lucas Lic. has some GIGANTIC shoes to fill with this dice rolling, Pokemon induced card game!  I hope you and your company you represent can stick to you promises and give a game worthy of Decipher's SWCCG.  I seriously doubt it.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF><a href="mailto:jeeps95@hotmail.com">Peter "jeeps" Jacobson</a></font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>one word comes to mind...greed...</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF><a href="mailto:efridge@epimp.com">efridge</a></font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>it is unfortunate that WotC and Decipher couldn't have come to an arrangement to have WotC get the current mechanics. I am a little worried about having dice in the game, but if it is a good change then I will play it.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Eby</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Hmmmm, no mention of the word "money,"  but of course that wouldn't be good for business now would it.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>Jeff Miller</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Wed Jan 9 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>How hard would it be to buy the SWCCG mechanics from Decipher so that a game could be made that maintained some backward compatibility?  The SWCCG had gotten a tad complex in many respects, but the core engine was still quite an elegant one, and all the game really needed was a second edition.<br>
<br>
I like the idea of Decipher releasing a game that uses the SWCCG mechanics on a non-licensed (or alternately licensed) property.  I heard a couple of ideas below... Final Fantasy was a good idea; the Matrix might be a good seller.  Or just release a game called 'space blasto' or something and the SWCCG community can keep buying cards to expand the environment of the current game.<br>
<br>
The new game may not fail, but I would put money on a wager that it won't succeed spectacularly, either.  The CCG market IS at a saturation point, or past it, and anyone who wants to play a Star Wars card game is already playing one, in many cases after investing thousands of dollars in it.  George Lucas is giving N Sync a cameo in Episode II to draw teenage females to see the movie; does WOTC plan to put naked pornstars on their card-backs to get players for their game?<br>
