<br>
Next, the fact that Lucasfilm fairly obviously was planning on selling rights to a card game to Wizards of the Coast (and probably forgoing rights to Decipher) brings no shame to Lucasfilm.  After all, the point that was made was that two companies COMPETED for the rights from another company.  Wizards, in some way, earned the rights by making a more promising offer to Lucasfilm.  Was the decision based on solely money?  We won't know.  Maybe they felt that Wizards WOULD do a better job.  Maybe they didn't like where Decipher was going with the game.  Even I must admit that some of the things that Warren Holland (Decipher's CEO) said they suggested to Lucasfilm were lousy ideas that I believe would hurt the game more than help it.<br>
But, I also do not feel, after reading the writings of both representitives for Decipher and Lucasfilm, that Lucasfilm did anything malicious to the players of Decipher's game.  Many people have responded to the Lucasfilm statement above with anger at Lucasfilm.  I believe that some of that is misdirected.  Who did not come forward and tell the players that the loss of the lisence was coming?  Who produced product with an implied promise that it might continue?  Which company did everything they could to hide the possible change in lisencing?  I do not believe that of the companies involved, Lucasfilm is the guilty party.  Neither is Wizards of the Coast who fairly competed for the rights to Star Wars using whatever free market abilities it had.<br>
<br>
Finally, I wanted to mention that of the things that I have read, Decipher wrote with scorn and malice.  Lucasfilm did not once speak poorly of the two companies competing for rights to Star Wars.  Decipher implied poor creativity and vision on the part of Wizards and Lucasfilm.  Lucasfilm attested above to the talent of Decipher's employees.  Decipher, as the producer of the game, supplied no information to the consumers until last minute.  Lucasfilm, not being the marketer of the game or any card game , released information upon the first web site update of the new year when Wizards first had legal rights to begin production of any type of product.<br>
<br>
I would welcome responses.</font></td></tr><tr><td><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>The Ithorian</font><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF> - Thu Jan 10 2002  </font></td></tr></table><p><table width=100%><tr><td><HR><font face=arial size=2 color=#FFFFFF>For the person saying how you had to have the Rares to build decks...<br><br>
